### VERDICTS
| Claim | Original verdict | Adversarial result (upheld/downgraded/refuted) | Revised verdict | Strongest counter-evidence (file:line) |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Typed failure taxonomy + pre-mortem | ADAPT, strong; ratio 0.74 | downgraded | ADAPT, weak/narrow: adopt only a unified pre-execution pre-mortem and, at most, consolidate existing scattered failure enums into a task-level contract | `.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence_recovery.md:46`, `.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence_recovery.md:101`, `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:512`, `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/post-dispatch-validate.ts:58` |

### EVIDENCE
- [V-016-01] Typed failure taxonomy: Refute the “only prose” framing. Spec-kit already has several typed failure/recovery models with retry/escalation behavior, just not one Gem-style global table. General rules provide hard halts and escalation triggers in `AGENTS.md:21-34` and confidence/logic-sync escalation in `AGENTS.md:301-316`. The orchestrator has explicit retry policy: attempts 1-2 retry, attempt 3 reassign, after 3+ escalate (`.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:512-516`); it classifies aborted/empty sub-agent output as `OVERLOAD` and forbids same-scope retry (`.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:518-526`); it has circuit-breaker states and per-scenario actions (`.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:528-537`). Deep-research has named stuck failure modes (`Search exhausted`, `Too narrow`, `Too broad`, `Contradictory evidence`, `State drift`) with typical responses (`.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence_recovery.md:46-55`), tiered recovery actions from retry source through user escalation (`.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence_recovery.md:101-109`), and escalation conditions (`.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/convergence/convergence_recovery.md:115-125`). The live loop classifies stuck modes as `shallow_sources`, `contradictory`, `too_broad`, `repetitive`, and `exhausted`, then logs `stuck_classified` (`.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md:343-357`). The deep-research agent has source-failure retry limits: alternative source, max 2 retries; then focus exhaustion and higher-tier escalation (`.opencode/agents/deep-research.md:185-188`, `.opencode/agents/deep-research.md:370-375`). Deep-loop runtime has typed dispatch failures: `timeout`, `crash`, `missing_output`, `invalid_output`, `other`, and recursion-guard reasons (`.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/executor-audit.ts:14-27`), emits typed `dispatch_failure` JSONL events (`.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/executor-audit.ts:545-574`), and translates timeout/crash/non-zero exit into typed events (`.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/executor-audit.ts:577-584`). Post-dispatch validation has a substantial typed failure enum: `iteration_file_missing`, `jsonl_not_appended`, `jsonl_parse_error`, `dispatch_failure_logged`, `verification_degraded`, and more (`.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/post-dispatch-validate.ts:58-75`). Deep-loop also has fallback routing for quota-pool failures (`.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/fallback-router.ts:31-76`), transient writer-lock retry (`.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/scripts/lib/cli-guards.cjs:166-198`), per-lineage timeout/non-zero failure classification plus salvage before throwing (`.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/scripts/fanout-run.cjs:453-479`), and fan-out failure isolation (`.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/scripts/fanout-pool.cjs:62-118`). Net: Gem’s exact taxonomy is cleaner and more centralized, but the claimed absence is false.
- [V-016-02] Pre-mortem: Mostly upheld, but narrower than claimed. Gem has an explicit `pre_mortem` schema required for MEDIUM/HIGH plans, with `overall_risk_level`, `critical_failure_modes`, likelihood, impact, mitigation, and assumptions (`specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-planner.agent.md:185-206`). Spec-kit has pre-execution planning/risk-adjacent mechanisms: “Plan before acting” (`AGENTS.md:59`), analysis lenses for systems/bias/sustainability/value/scope (`AGENTS.md:142-151`), orchestrator pre-delegation reasoning with mandatory `Risk: Low/Medium/High` and high-risk fallback (`.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:222-236`), and deep-research charter validation for Non-Goals and Stop Conditions before proceeding (`.opencode/skills/deep-research/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md:82-88`). However, grep found no live `.opencode/skills/deep-research`, `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime`, or `.opencode/agents` pre-mortem/premortem contract; hits were in the current research packet or external corpora. So the genuine gap is not “resilience” broadly; it is an explicit mandatory pre-execution risk/failure-mode/assumption field for medium/high tasks.

### REVISED NET-NEW VALUE
The sub-packet-worthy value is a small agent-runtime governance refinement, not a deep-loop-runtime resilience overhaul. Add a mandatory pre-execution pre-mortem field to orchestrator/PDR for medium/high work, reusing existing `Risk` and fallback fields: risk level, top 2-3 critical failure modes, assumptions, mitigations, and approval/blockers. Optionally normalize existing scattered failure enums into a shared task-level `failure_type` output contract, but do not import Gem’s taxonomy wholesale; deep-research and deep-loop already have domain-specific typed recovery, retry limits, fallback routing, timeout handling, salvage, and escalation.

